<SerialLayout
	title="The Nikon FE2 — the unsung hero of Civil War — Serial"
	description="A working review of the Nikon FE2: the shutter, three Nikkors on test, and a note on shooting Portra 800."
>
	<Nav />

	<Hero
		kicker="Gear / 35mm"
		category="Review"
		title="The Nikon FE2 — the unsung hero of Civil War"
		image={{ src: "/images/serial/hero-fe2-topplate.jpg", alt: "Close-up of the Nikon FE2 top plate, showing the FE2 nameplate and shutter speed dial" }}
	/>

	<div class="wrap">
		<div class="section" style="padding-top:56px">
			<p class="lede">
				<span class="drop">In light of how much camera nerdery hides inside a war film,</span> the
				most quietly capable body in Civil War (2024) isn't a prop — it's the Nikon FE2 slung around
				Jessie's neck. A mechanical-hearted 35mm SLR that keeps working after the batteries die,
				syncs faster than it should, and steals a scene from Cailee Spaeny without saying a word.
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>

	<ImageGrid
		variant="2"
		tiles={[
			{
				tag: "FE2",
				image: { src: "/images/serial/fe2-front-50mm.jpg", alt: "The Nikon FE2 with the Nikkor 50mm 1.4 mounted" },
			},
			{
				tag: "Civil War '24",
				image: { src: "/images/serial/civil-war-jessie.jpg", alt: "Cailee Spaeny as Jessie in Civil War (2024), shooting the Nikon FE2" },
			},
		]}
	/>

	<ArticleSection number="01" title="The Body">
		<p>
			The headline trick is the shutter — a titanium-bladed unit that tops out at 1/4000 and,
			crucially, flash-syncs at 1/250. That's unusually quick for 1983, and it's what makes the
			FE2 a working tool rather than a nostalgia object: you can drag daylight down with fast glass
			wide open, and balance fill-flash against a bright sky without fighting the sync.
		</p>
		<p>
			It's aperture-priority with a proper manual mode, and the mechanical heart means the shutter
			still fires at 1/250 if the batteries give out mid-roll — the meter goes dark, the picture
			doesn't. Compact, dense, honest in the hand. Nothing about it tries to impress you, which is
			exactly why it does.
		</p>
	</ArticleSection>

	<PullQuote
		quote="The camera that keeps working after the meter dies, the flash misses, and the moment refuses to wait."
	/>

	<ArticleSection number="02" title="Glass — Three Nikkors on Test">
		<p style="margin-bottom:20px">
			A body is only as good as what you hang on it, and the FE2's F-mount opens onto decades of
			Nikkor glass. I've been living with three: a nifty-fifty, a modern-ish wide, and a genuinely
			old character piece.
		</p>
	</ArticleSection>

	<ImageGrid
		variant="wide"
		tiles={[
			{
				aspect: "16 / 6",
				image: {
					src: "/images/serial/three-nikkors.jpg",
					alt: "Three Nikkor lenses lined up in front of the FE2 body: the 24mm 2.8, 50mm 1.4, and vintage 28mm f/2",
				},
			},
		]}
	/>

	<LensSpec
		name="Nikkor 50mm 1:1.4"
		sn="S/N 5161507"
		rows={[
			{ k: "Aperture", v: "f/1.4" },
			{ k: "Use", v: "Everyday / low light" },
		]}
		verdict="The safe keeper"
	>
		The default answer, and a good one. Fast enough to shoot Portra 800 indoors without flinching;
		classic Nikon rendering — a touch of glow wide open, clinical by f/2.8. The lens you leave on
		when you don't know what the day holds.
	</LensSpec>

	<LensSpec
		name="Nikkor 24mm 1:2.8"
		sn="S/N 650791"
		rows={[
			{ k: "Aperture", v: "f/2.8" },
			{ k: "Use", v: "Street / reportage" },
		]}
		verdict="Current favourite"
	>
		My favourite so far. Wide enough to put you inside the scene rather than observing it, but not
		so wide it distorts — the focal length that makes street and documentary work feel present. If I
		could keep one, it's this, no hesitation.
	</LensSpec>

	<LensSpec
		name="Nikkor-N Auto 28mm f/2"
		sn="Nippon Kogaku &middot; No. 281872"
		rows={[
			{ k: "Aperture", v: "f/2" },
			{ k: "Era", v: "Vintage Nippon Kogaku" },
		]}
		verdict="Jury still out"
	>
		The wildcard — a genuinely old Nippon Kogaku piece with the build and character to match. On
		paper the sweet spot between the 24 and the 50; in practice I haven't run enough rolls through it
		to call it. Early frames promising. Verdict pending.
	</LensSpec>

