	<ArticleSection number="03" title="A Note on Film — Portra 800">
		<p>
			A body and glass are half the picture; the other half is what you load. Right now I shoot
			<a href="#">Kodak Portra 800</a> almost exclusively, and the FE2 is the perfect delivery system
			for it. The low-light performance is the reason — at box speed it holds shadow detail and skin
			tones no faster stock touches, and the colours are simply gorgeous, warm without being fake.
		</p>
		<p>
			Yes, it blows out in broad daylight and reads overexposed — but I've come to love the vibe on
			those frames too. That golden, slightly-too-bright wash is a look, not a flaw. The only real
			problem is scarcity: true ISO 800 alternatives are thin on the ground, I don't get on with
			Cinestill, and there's not much to switch to. My wallet isn't thrilled. The results make the
			argument anyway.
		</p>
		<p>
			The one exception lives in my pocket — the point-and-shoot runs <a href="#">Ultramax 400</a>,
			because there's no sense feeding premium stock to a fixed lens. Everything else gets the good
			stuff.
		</p>
	</ArticleSection>

